WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.941 --> 00:00:07.480
[Music]

00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:16.480
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today we're going&nbsp;
to look at graphing polynomials. This is a way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:25.600
of associating a visual geometrical object with&nbsp;
what's up till now been a purely algebraic object.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:32.560
Once we do that, we can interpret the tangents&nbsp;
that we defined last time—the various key tangents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:39.320
of a polynomial: first tangent, second tangent,&nbsp;
third tangent, and so on. We can interpret those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:48.400
geometrically as tangent lines, tangent conics,&nbsp;
which are approximating the polynomial at a point.

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:53.480
Now, I'm going to increasingly be using the&nbsp;
"polynomial" word rather than the "poly number"&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:59.920
word to make contact with more classical&nbsp;
mathematics, but I hope you keep in mind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:07.480
that for us, a polynomial is just another word&nbsp;
for a poly number. So, when it comes down to it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:16.680
a polynomial like this is essentially just a&nbsp;
list of numbers—the list of the coefficients&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:21.520
of the various powers of alpha. And today,&nbsp;
we're going to be talking about just those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:29.920
polynomials with integer coefficients, so-called&nbsp;
integral polynomials or integral poly numbers.

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:40.480
So our idea of representing such a polynomial&nbsp;
graphically is to plot the values of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:50.520
pairs of numbers and the polynomial values at&nbsp;
those numbers. That way, we get a two-dimensional&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:58.880
representation that somehow incorporates&nbsp;
or allows us to visualize the polynomial.

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:03.440
Let's start off by having a look at this&nbsp;
particular polynomial and calculating some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:10.520
of these values of the polynomial at various&nbsp;
constants. Here, on the left-hand side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:18.480
I've listed various integers from -5 up to&nbsp;
10, and I've computed for you the values of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.480 --> 00:02:28.520
this polynomial at the various constants. So, this&nbsp;
-166 here means that if you replace alpha with -3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:39.400
then this evaluates to -166. So, our idea&nbsp;
is to graph pairs of such numbers in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:46.120
two-dimensional setting, and for that, we're&nbsp;
going to go back to Cartesian coordinates.

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:51.520
This is a way of introducing geometry&nbsp;
in a very concrete and explicit way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:59.960
using essentially a sheet of graph paper with&nbsp;
equally spaced horizontal and vertical lines&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:08.480
forming this pattern of unit cells or squares. We&nbsp;
can write a distinguished horizontal line and call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:14.680
it the x-axis (the usual convention), and we can&nbsp;
distinguish a particular vertical line and call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:24.480
it the y-axis. We can label these various nodes&nbsp;
here: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, and so on in that direction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:32.880
-1, -2, -3, and so on in this direction, and going&nbsp;
up: 1, 2, 3, 4; going down: -1, -2, -3, and so on.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:40.840
The idea is that if we have a point like this&nbsp;
one here, then we can look at the x-coordinate,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:47.240
which is 1, and we can look at the y-coordinate,&nbsp;
which is 6, and then we can essentially give this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:56.600
point a name by associating it with the pair (1,&nbsp;
6) enclosed in square brackets by convention. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:02.040
we can define a mathematical object called&nbsp;
an integer point, which is just a pair of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:08.320
integers enclosed in square brackets, and it's an&nbsp;
ordered pair. So, there's a first one and a second&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:14.720
one corresponding to the x-coordinate and the&nbsp;
y-coordinate. That defines a new type of object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:21.440
which we might call "Int²," an integer point.&nbsp;
And then a variant on that is when we do exactly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:28.880
the same thing but we allow the numbers in the&nbsp;
brackets to be rational numbers. In that case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:36.960
we get a rational point, and this new&nbsp;
type of object we can call "Rat²" or,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:44.640
for simplicity, just a point. So, a point is&nbsp;
generally just a pair of rational numbers.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:52.800
So, there's (0, 6); there's a point (0, 3);&nbsp;
there's (-1, 0); there's (-2, -3). We can also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.680 --> 00:05:00.400
talk about points that are not necessarily&nbsp;
on the intersections, but sort of with more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:07.720
random positions. One of the lovely things about&nbsp;
this Cartesian coordinate system, essentially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:15.280
introduced around the time of Descartes, is&nbsp;
that we can encode lines and other nice curves,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:21.800
like conics, pleasantly in an algebraic form. So,&nbsp;
for example, this line here, which goes through&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:30.000
these various points—equally spaced: 1 over 3 up,&nbsp;
1 over 3 up, 1 over 3 up—so this really is a line.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:39.080
This line can be described by the relation between&nbsp;
the x- and y-coordinates of the points on it.

00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:44.760
A usual kind of description is in terms of an&nbsp;
equation that we can write like this: in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:53.160
case, 3x - y + 3 = 0. Every point on this&nbsp;
line happens to satisfy this equation. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:59.960
for example, (1, 6)—if you replace x with&nbsp;
1 and y with 6, then you get 3 - 6 + 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.960 --> 00:06:05.920
which is indeed zero. So, this point satisfies&nbsp;
the equation, telling us this point is on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:13.880
line. You could check that all these points lie on&nbsp;
the line in the sense of satisfying the equation.

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:18.560
Now, the x and the y are in some sense arbitrary;&nbsp;
they're not really necessary. The central&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:23.840
ingredients are the various coefficients that&nbsp;
appear here, and we like to abbreviate them by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:32.080
just talking about their proportion: 3 to -1 to 3.&nbsp;
That encodes the line just as well as that does,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:36.280
and the pointy brackets sort of alert us to&nbsp;
the fact that we're talking about an Euclidean&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.280 --> 00:06:46.680
line. So, we can talk about lines, and we can talk&nbsp;
about points in this Cartesian coordinate system.

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:52.960
Now, maybe it's useful to say here that the&nbsp;
algebraic side of things—when we're talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:59.520
points like this or points like this and lines&nbsp;
like this—doesn't actually require a picture.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:09.160
The picture is a physical object that is, strictly&nbsp;
speaking, outside the world of mathematics. It&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:17.080
resides here in the physical world in which we&nbsp;
live. We're making various assumptions when we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:24.560
work with a picture like this, and we're also&nbsp;
disregarding certain subtleties. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:30.240
we're not fussing about exactly how wide&nbsp;
these lines are, we're not fussing too much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:37.600
about exactly how big the points are that we're&nbsp;
drawing, and we're also kind of assuming that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:44.480
it is possible, in fact, to create a pattern&nbsp;
like this where these lines actually are all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:49.240
equally spaced and, by implication, where&nbsp;
they're all parallel. So, even if we were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:56.920
to extend these lines indefinitely, they would&nbsp;
not meet—it's our idea of parallelism. The same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.920 --> 00:08:03.640
for the vertical lines. But that's really an&nbsp;
assumption about the world in which we live,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:09.880
which may or may not be completely&nbsp;
true. It's a kind of an important point.

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:14.840
So, let me just say a little bit more about&nbsp;
that. Imagine for a second that we're living&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:20.360
on a round planet. Well, okay, we are,&nbsp;
but imagine that this round planet was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:26.120
completely smooth and didn't have any objects&nbsp;
on it other than perhaps ourselves. Otherwise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.120 --> 00:08:34.480
it was a completely smooth, featureless Earth,&nbsp;
for example, perhaps something like this. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:41.080
imagine this is a model of the Earth, and perhaps&nbsp;
you and I are right there—we're very, very tiny—so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:48.240
that as we look at the Earth, it's locally quite&nbsp;
flat and we see what looks to us like a plane.

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:54.000
Now, suppose that we attempted on this&nbsp;
surface to draw such a grid plane. That&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.760
would be a natural thing to do. We might make&nbsp;
some strings and try to make some parallel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:08.600
lines, okay? And then some ones which are&nbsp;
perpendicular, parallel lines like this. But if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:16.760
started examining the geometry of this grid plane&nbsp;
that we're making on the surface of the sphere,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.760 --> 00:09:25.800
we would discover that it differs from this&nbsp;
one subtly in measurable ways. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:30.280
the lines that we are, for example, thinking&nbsp;
are parallel—if we actually stand to them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:36.920
we would find very likely that they meet.&nbsp;
Or, we would find that these two lines are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:41.400
perpendicular to this one, but if we move&nbsp;
this line up and say to that one there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:47.760
then these two lines are no longer perpendicular&nbsp;
to it, which is quite different from our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:53.720
assumptions about this thing in the Euclidean&nbsp;
plane. So, in other words, there are assumptions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.720 --> 00:10:02.040
about the physical world built into a model of&nbsp;
this graph paper that we have in our booklets.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:02.040 --> 00:10:08.840
It's not entirely obvious that a piece of&nbsp;
graph paper exists. Well, yes, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:17.400
it looks like it exists in your notebook, but if&nbsp;
you made a very, very careful measurement of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:22.880
various relationships between these lines and the&nbsp;
various perpendicularities, you might find that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:29.320
the curvature of the universe somehow makes them&nbsp;
not as perfectly aligned as we think they are.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:35.960
There's a bit of a can of worms that we have&nbsp;
to recognize that we don't really know the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:40.880
true geometry of the world in which&nbsp;
we live, and since the 20th century,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:44.760
Einstein has taught us that the geometry&nbsp;
of the world in which we live is, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:52.040
much more complicated than we used to think it&nbsp;
is. There is such a thing as curvature, and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.040 --> 00:10:58.560
true overall structure is far from settled, but&nbsp;
in particular, it's probably pretty obvious that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:06.960
it's not completely Euclidean and straightforward&nbsp;
the way people used to think 100 or 200 years ago.

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:13.040
So we have to separate in our minds the&nbsp;
mathematical model that we're working with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:16.680
the theory that we're developing,&nbsp;
and these pictures that we're drawing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:21.800
to help us visualize the mathematics.&nbsp;
This is an important point—that for us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:29.520
the expressions that we will write down will&nbsp;
be primary, logically. They take precedence.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:35.560
These pictures are just for us&nbsp;
aids in understanding things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:43.400
and we must be careful not to too quickly draw&nbsp;
mathematical conclusions from the pictures that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:52.840
draw. It's something to be aware of—a potential&nbsp;
difficulty with relying too much on pictures.

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:57.920
So this is the point I've just made: that the&nbsp;
physical existence of a sheet of graph paper is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.920 --> 00:12:04.160
separate from the mathematical model of integer&nbsp;
points or rational points that we can work with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:11.960
algebraically. And there are empirical questions&nbsp;
or technological issues associated with the graph&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:18.720
paper and constructions on it. For example, is a&nbsp;
sheet of graph paper really Euclidean? That's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:23.840
issue we've already talked about. Do we live in&nbsp;
a curved world? How does that affect the actual&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:29.760
properties of a piece of graph paper? Another&nbsp;
question is, can we extend such a sheet of graph&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:35.440
paper? In many of our constructions, we might be&nbsp;
interested in extending the axes, perhaps quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:42.000
a long way to deal with very big numbers or very&nbsp;
small negative numbers. So, a natural question is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:49.400
to what extent can we extend this graph paper?&nbsp;
Obviously, there are physical barriers because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:53.800
we're living on a planet Earth of only a&nbsp;
certain size, and of course, in practice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.800 --> 00:12:59.880
it's hard to get a piece of paper that's too&nbsp;
big. But even theoretically, the large-scale&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:05.840
structure of the universe may actually be kind of&nbsp;
closed. There may not be room, even theoretically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:12.760
in the universe to have a sheet of graph&nbsp;
paper that, for example, extends indefinitely.

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:19.160
Another sort of related or inverse question&nbsp;
to that one is, can we subdivide a sheet of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.160 --> 00:13:25.160
graph paper arbitrarily? Suppose we&nbsp;
want to create a finer mesh by, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.160 --> 00:13:31.640
subdividing each of our squares into ten little&nbsp;
pieces, and then we want a yet finer one where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:39.040
we subdivide even those smaller squares into ten&nbsp;
little pieces, and so on. Can we keep doing that?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:45.240
Well, theoretically we can, but in practice,&nbsp;
empirically, in the world in which we live,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.120 --> 00:13:52.080
once we get down to very small scales, the&nbsp;
laws of physics start becoming quite strange,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.080 --> 00:14:00.200
and we arrive at limitations of our ability to&nbsp;
resolve quantities, and quantum effects start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:07.080
interfering with our measurement. So, in the real&nbsp;
world, you can't keep subdividing things. Or,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.080 --> 00:14:12.480
to put it another way, when you subdivide things,&nbsp;
things change. The laws of physics start changing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.480 --> 00:14:20.120
on you, and you enter a world that is quite&nbsp;
different from the way it is in our experience.

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:26.440
So there actually are quite deep questions&nbsp;
of a physical nature—the physical nature&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:26.440 --> 00:14:30.520
of the continuum or the large-scale&nbsp;
structure of the universe—connected&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.360 --> 00:14:37.240
with a sheet of graph paper and what we&nbsp;
actually can do with it practically. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:37.240 --> 00:14:42.200
one way of dealing with these issues is to say,&nbsp;
all right, we're going to think of these graphs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:47.280
that we're going to draw and the pictures that&nbsp;
we make as simply aids to our understanding,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:51.760
and that we're going to draw a line between&nbsp;
the logic of what we're doing algebraically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:56.960
and the pictures that we're going to draw to&nbsp;
help us understand things and maybe guide our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:56.960 --> 00:15:02.200
intuition. Because we are actually very&nbsp;
visual creatures, we have a lot of brain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:11.720
processing devoted to visuals, so it makes&nbsp;
sense to use that; it's one of our strengths.

00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:20.840
So let's go back to our polynomial, this one&nbsp;
here, and let's try to graph it. Here are these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:27.080
various values that we've already computed.&nbsp;
So, here are now the pairs of numbers that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:27.080 --> 00:15:33.360
would like to graph—these are sort of integer&nbsp;
points, and there's a range of them. And one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:39.120
thing that we see is that the y-coordinates,&nbsp;
the second coordinates, are actually, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:45.680
they get quite big, especially big negative.&nbsp;
So, if we're going to hope to picture them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:54.000
we should scale our grid in a rather different&nbsp;
way than what we did before. And we have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.920
allow ourselves this flexibility to&nbsp;
scale the two axes in different ways.

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:08.200
So here, the x-axis has been scaled so this is one&nbsp;
unit: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, and so on. However, the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:18.680
y-axis has been scaled dramatically different—this&nbsp;
now represents 100. So: 100, 200, 300, 400, 500,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:26.960
that's 1,000, that's -500, that's -1,000. Now,&nbsp;
I haven't drawn all the lines because to do so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:32.840
would require thousands of lines. So we're going&nbsp;
to adopt the convention that we're going to forget&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:37.720
about all the lines—horizontal and vertical—except&nbsp;
for the two axes themselves, and we're just going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:49.680
to use parallel lines to locate the positions of&nbsp;
points. So let's graph these points: -5, -192;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.680 --> 00:17:02.600
so -5, and then -192 is about there; and then this&nbsp;
point: -4, -484, about there; -3, -166; -2, -30;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:02.600 --> 00:17:11.520
-1, 8; 0, 8 actually has the same y-value;&nbsp;
1, 6 going down just a little bit; 2, 24 up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:21.360
a little bit; 3, 320 up a little bit more;&nbsp;
then down 4, -25; 5, -42; 6, -454; and 7,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.920 --> 00:17:37.320
-116. So these various points that we've drawn now&nbsp;
are, in some sense, a picture of this polynomial.

00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:39.600
Now, you might not be used to that&nbsp;
kind of picture—you might be used to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:39.600 --> 00:17:46.320
a more continuous picture—but if&nbsp;
we're working over the integers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.320 --> 00:17:52.600
which we can suppose we're at least initially&nbsp;
doing, then this is a very reasonable picture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:52.600 --> 00:17:58.840
because in our minds there are only integers,&nbsp;
and we're just plotting various integer points.

00:18:01.080 --> 00:18:07.200
Of course, we're not plotting a lot of integer&nbsp;
points—we're not plotting any of those points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:07.200 --> 00:18:16.600
with an x-coordinate more than 6 or a y-coordinate&nbsp;
less than 6. So in fact, this is just some very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:24.600
small fraction of a much bigger picture that we&nbsp;
could extend far in either direction if we had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:24.600 --> 00:18:31.520
the patience and the room to do so. And maybe&nbsp;
also the computing power, because perhaps it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:40.840
would get quite involved to compute these things&nbsp;
if the x's become very big or very big negative.

00:18:40.840 --> 00:18:47.000
So this is a graph; it's not the only graph&nbsp;
that we can draw. It's a kind of a partial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:54.200
graph—it only encodes part of the picture—but&nbsp;
nevertheless, it's some kind of physical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:58.880
representation that we can look at and say, ah,&nbsp;
there's some kind of pattern here. It's almost&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:04.920
just like some dynamical thing moving. We&nbsp;
might say it's an integral graph because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:13.040
all the points that we're plotting have&nbsp;
integer coordinates. But a lot of times we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:18.480
are interested in not just integral values&nbsp;
but also rational values—in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:24.520
points with rational coordinates.&nbsp;
So let's say a few words about them.

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:28.880
Suppose, for example, that we're&nbsp;
interested in the standard grid&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:35.200
plane here, where now the x-axis is here, the&nbsp;
y-axis is here, and suppose we're interested in,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:45.280
say, plotting a point like this with&nbsp;
rational coordinates: 9/2 and 5/3. 9/2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:53.200
5/3—well, one way to do that is to say&nbsp;
9/2 is exactly halfway between 4 and 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:53.200 --> 00:20:01.760
so we'll draw some point halfway between 4 and&nbsp;
5, and 5/3 is, well, somewhere between 1 and 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:06.560
and we'll do it roughly. But we would like&nbsp;
to do it exactly because we would like to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:06.560 --> 00:20:14.520
be completely correct here. So how do we&nbsp;
construct such a point? It's important to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:22.680
realize that we can construct such a point with&nbsp;
just lines connecting existing points in our grid&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:28.640
plane. So I'm going to show you how to do it for&nbsp;
this point, and I hope you'll see the pattern.

00:20:30.320 --> 00:20:36.960
To get 9/2, first of all, on the x-axis here,&nbsp;
what I'm going to do is I'm going to consider&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:36.960 --> 00:20:45.360
a rectangle—this one right here—which is 9 over&nbsp;
and 2 up. So that point there is the point with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:51.600
coordinates 9/2, and I'm going to connect that&nbsp;
point to the origin with this green line. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:51.600 --> 00:20:58.600
where that green line crosses the line&nbsp;
x = 1, because this is exactly halfway,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:59.720 --> 00:21:11.120
this will be exactly halfway there. So this will&nbsp;
be the coordinate 4.5, or 9/2. In a similar way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:11.120 --> 00:21:18.040
if we want to get 5/3 in this direction, what&nbsp;
I do is I make a rectangle that goes 5 this way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:23.960
and 3 this way. So this rectangle right here—this&nbsp;
is the point with y-coordinate 5 and x-coordinate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:23.960 --> 00:21:32.600
3. I draw the line connecting the origin, and I&nbsp;
see where that line meets the line x = 1. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:42.080
in that point there—so what is its y-coordinate?&nbsp;
Well, this is 1/3 of the way from here to here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:51.400
that's 1/3 of the way, and so this will be 1/3 of&nbsp;
the way to here. So that point there will be 5/3.

00:21:51.400 --> 00:21:58.680
And all we needed to do that was to connect points&nbsp;
that are already in the grid plane to create&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:04.480
that line and to create that line and see where&nbsp;
those two lines cross—lines that are part of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:11.280
grid plane. So once, of course, we have the&nbsp;
x-coordinate here and the y-coordinate here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:20.320
it's not too hard to make parallel lines&nbsp;
which then give us the required point.

00:22:20.320 --> 00:22:27.000
So with this technique in hand, we can now&nbsp;
extend our view of a polynomial. We can now say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:33.480
all right, let's try to visualize a polynomial&nbsp;
p by plotting many points of the form (c, p(c)),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:42.280
where c now are suitably chosen rational numbers&nbsp;
in a certain chosen range. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:42.280 --> 00:22:47.320
we don't have to stick with integer&nbsp;
values of c—we can substitute more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:47.320 --> 00:22:51.880
general rational values and plot those points.

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:58.560
So now let's have another look at our&nbsp;
favorite polynomial, this one right here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:04.000
The existing points that we have already drawn,&nbsp;
the ones with integer values in this range,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:12.480
are right there. Now I'm going to add some new&nbsp;
points—the green ones—whose x-coordinates are 1/2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:17.920
-1/2, 3/2, -3/2, in other words, sort of&nbsp;
halfway between the various points that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:27.920
we already have. So if I plug in 1/2 into here&nbsp;
and compute, I get 95/16. And when I plot that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:38.400
there's the x-coordinate 1/2, 95/16—that's roughly&nbsp;
about six, and so with those two coordinates,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:44.320
we can plot that point there. There it is there,&nbsp;
right in that green. And I've also plotted -1/2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:46.120 --> 00:24:07.720
159/16, 3/2, and 143/16, -3/2 and -49/16, 5/2,&nbsp;
which is there, and -5/2, 303/16, -7/2—that's 3.5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:26.280
that's this one over here with 191/16, and 9/2&nbsp;
and -961/16—that's just barely in our range.

00:24:26.280 --> 00:24:32.880
So we have these new green points now to augment&nbsp;
the red ones that we already have. And now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:36.360
because I'm interested in the rational&nbsp;
graph, what I'm going to do is I'm going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:43.800
to do a time-honored technique that goes back&nbsp;
to primary school, or probably even earlier:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:49.400
we are going to join the dots. We're going to&nbsp;
take our ruler or our straight edge and just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:49.400 --> 00:24:56.440
join these adjacent points, because they're&nbsp;
all one after the other in a certain order,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:56.440 --> 00:25:02.320
join them up with this black line—just&nbsp;
straight line segments from one to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:13.360
next—and then we get some kind of&nbsp;
picture of a part of the polynomial.

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:20.440
Of course, this is not a complete picture; it's&nbsp;
not complete for two different opposing reasons.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:27.040
It's important to appreciate both of these ways&nbsp;
in which this is not complete. It's not complete,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.040 --> 00:25:32.440
first of all, because we only went from here&nbsp;
to here. All the values to the right here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:38.240
all the values to the left here were not included&nbsp;
in the picture. We could have included some more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.240 --> 00:25:46.240
of them by making the paper larger or perhaps&nbsp;
by scaling our axes appropriately. But no matter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:46.240 --> 00:25:50.400
how we do that, no matter how big a piece of&nbsp;
paper we have, no matter how much we scale,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:58.520
we still only get always a finite part of&nbsp;
a bigger picture. It's always possible to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.520 --> 00:26:03.520
extend the picture, so we never&nbsp;
get the whole picture this way.

00:26:03.520 --> 00:26:09.120
There's another way in which we don't get the&nbsp;
whole picture: because we've only subdivided&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:09.120 --> 00:26:15.520
each one of these intervals into, in this case,&nbsp;
two pieces. Now, I could come along and say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:20.120
well, I'm going to do a better job; I'm going&nbsp;
to subdivide each one of these intervals into,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:20.120 --> 00:26:28.560
say, ten pieces. So I could calculate&nbsp;
ten different values and plot them all;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:28.560 --> 00:26:34.960
then I would get a much finer resolution.&nbsp;
But still, it would only be a partial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:39.400
picture. There's still a resolution here,&nbsp;
and between the points that I'm plotting,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.400 --> 00:26:48.280
I'm not really getting the accurate values—I'm&nbsp;
replacing the values with straight line segments.

00:26:48.280 --> 00:26:55.080
Actually, if you have a computer program that&nbsp;
plots curves like this, it might even dispense&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:55.080 --> 00:27:01.680
entirely with drawing little line segments.&nbsp;
If the number of points is sufficiently large,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:07.680
if I divided each one of these pieces&nbsp;
into, say, 100 and plotted all the points,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:07.680 --> 00:27:13.480
then those points would probably run together,&nbsp;
forming what looks to you like a continuous curve.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:13.480 --> 00:27:21.800
There'd be no need to make little adjoining&nbsp;
lines. So, in fact, mathematics programs that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:28.400
do make calculations do almost exactly this:&nbsp;
they use a "join the dots" method, or they just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:38.880
deal with dots themselves, sort of a pixel&nbsp;
approach or like a vector graphics approach.

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:43.680
But the important thing to realize is that even&nbsp;
if the picture that your computer is outputting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:51.160
looks very smooth, it's an illusion. It&nbsp;
is not the real picture; it is a picture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:51.160 --> 00:27:58.560
that has been derived by going to a certain&nbsp;
resolution and no further—just the way it is.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:05.200
It's just as impossible to plot all the points in&nbsp;
one of these little intervals as it is impossible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:05.200 --> 00:28:15.280
to plot all the points on the whole line, whatever&nbsp;
those terms even mean. We can go a certain way in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:15.280 --> 00:28:21.480
both directions, and that's just the natural&nbsp;
limitations of this mathematical problem.

00:28:21.480 --> 00:28:27.400
So this picture here that I'm drawing is actually&nbsp;
very representative of what actually happens in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:27.400 --> 00:28:33.640
practice, and there's no need to be ashamed&nbsp;
of drawing straight line segments. That way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:33.640 --> 00:28:39.000
we stick with something that's completely&nbsp;
concrete. I could have tried to sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:45.360
artistically draw a curve through there, but that&nbsp;
would be a bit sloppy because I would probably&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:45.360 --> 00:28:50.720
not do a very good job, and also, if I did it&nbsp;
again the next day, the curve that I drew would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:50.720 --> 00:28:56.920
be probably noticeably different from the curve&nbsp;
I drew today. So it's not really reproducible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:56.920 --> 00:29:03.040
and it's also very difficult to specify to you&nbsp;
what exactly I have done—sorry if I'm taking a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:08.920
picture—but here, you can specify this and pass&nbsp;
the instructions over the internet to someone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:08.920 --> 00:29:16.560
else, and they can create more or less the same&nbsp;
diagram, subject to the actual widths of points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:16.560 --> 00:29:25.480
and widths of lines that you're going to use.&nbsp;
So this is the essence of plotting polynomials.

00:29:25.480 --> 00:29:31.480
Now, let's turn our hand to some interesting&nbsp;
applications involving tangents. At the end&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:35.680
of the last lecture, I gave you an exercise&nbsp;
to do, which I strongly encouraged you to do,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:35.680 --> 00:29:43.680
which was to calculate various&nbsp;
tangents to this cubic polynomial:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:52.200
5 - 3 alpha - 4 alpha^2 + alpha^3. So let's&nbsp;
have a look at some of those tangents,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:52.200 --> 00:29:58.160
and you can compare with what I've got to see&nbsp;
if I've gotten the right answer. And I'm also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:58.160 --> 00:30:05.680
going to graph not just the original&nbsp;
cubic but also various tangents.

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:12.360
The original cubic p is plotted here,&nbsp;
so this sort of signifies the coding:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:12.360 --> 00:30:20.560
the red points and the black lines.&nbsp;
I'm just using integer points here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:25.520
so you can think of this, if you like, as&nbsp;
being essentially over the integers—integral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:25.520 --> 00:30:31.040
points—and I'm joining the dots between these&nbsp;
integral points. And beyond these ranges,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:31.040 --> 00:30:39.320
the numbers go off my scale, which goes&nbsp;
roughly from 20 to -20, or maybe to around -30.

00:30:39.320 --> 00:30:48.040
Okay, let's consider the various tangents to this&nbsp;
at the point zero. Those are the simplest to read&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:48.040 --> 00:30:54.840
off because they just correspond to truncating&nbsp;
this expression in various ways. The simplest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:54.840 --> 00:31:00.680
truncation is when we ignore all of those things,&nbsp;
and we just get the zeroth tangent at zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:00.680 --> 00:31:10.800
which is just five. Well, that's also a poly&nbsp;
number or polynomial, and we can plot it also.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:10.800 --> 00:31:17.520
It's very simple to plot—it just turns out to be&nbsp;
this line. Why? Because we're plotting all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:25.440
points of the form c and this thing evaluated at&nbsp;
c, but this thing evaluated at c is always five,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:33.480
so we're plotting (1, 5), (2, 5), (3, 5), (4, 5),&nbsp;
and so on—all of the points just along this line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:33.480 --> 00:31:46.520
where the y-coordinate is five. So there's the&nbsp;
zeroth tangent to this cubic at the point zero.

00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:51.880
The first tangent is what we get when we&nbsp;
disregard everything except the constant&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:51.880 --> 00:31:57.840
and the linear terms—that's 5 - 3&nbsp;
alpha. That's a linear polynomial,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:58.400 --> 00:32:07.040
and what does that look like? Well, it looks&nbsp;
like this line right here with the blue dots and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:07.040 --> 00:32:17.240
the red line. It is a line; it's the line y = 5 -&nbsp;
3x, if you like to think in terms of x and y. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:17.240 --> 00:32:25.320
for example, when x is zero, then we get&nbsp;
the value five; when x is one or alpha is 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:25.320 --> 00:32:35.800
we get the value two; when alpha is&nbsp;
two, we get the value -1, and so on.

00:32:35.800 --> 00:32:44.040
The second tangent to the polynomial at zero is&nbsp;
what we get when we just drop that cubic term,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:44.040 --> 00:32:54.640
so it's 5 - 3 alpha - 4 alpha^2, and we can&nbsp;
plot that also for different values: -1, 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:54.640 --> 00:33:01.160
-2, and so on. We can plug it into here&nbsp;
and get the corresponding y-coordinate,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:08.240
and I've graphed them for you. So there's&nbsp;
this point here, this one, this one, this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:08.240 --> 00:33:16.280
this one, and this one—those are the values&nbsp;
that are graphed in the range that I've drawn.

00:33:16.280 --> 00:33:27.760
So, to summarize, the original cubic is&nbsp;
pictured by these points; the zeroth tangent is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:29.600 --> 00:33:37.280
plotted by these points or that sort of horizontal&nbsp;
line; the first tangent, or the tangent line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:37.280 --> 00:33:48.160
is plotted by these points; and the second&nbsp;
tangent line, or the tangent conic at zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:57.840
is represented or graphed by those points. So&nbsp;
you can see that this is a purely integral graph.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:57.840 --> 00:34:01.920
This is a picture that you could draw&nbsp;
even if you did not know what fractions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:10.760
were—if you only knew arithmetic with&nbsp;
integers, you could draw this picture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:10.760 --> 00:34:20.280
and you can see some shape, and some patterns,&nbsp;
even though we're only working over the integers.

00:34:20.280 --> 00:34:26.640
Now let's have a look at the same curve, but from&nbsp;
the point of view of a different point—not zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:31.680
but we'll choose another point. Let's say the&nbsp;
point two and see what the various tangents to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:31.680 --> 00:34:37.360
the same curve look like at the point two—in&nbsp;
other words, sort of at this point here.

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:46.240
So the tangents at two I asked you to compute last&nbsp;
time, and it turns out that the zeroth tangent at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:46.240 --> 00:34:55.240
two is the constant -9, the first tangent at two&nbsp;
is 5 - 7 alpha, and the second tangent at two is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:55.240 --> 00:35:06.400
133 - 15 alpha + 2 alpha^2, and I've plotted&nbsp;
those for you: -9—that's the horizontal line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:06.400 --> 00:35:16.840
consisting of these green points; the tangent line&nbsp;
5 - 7 alpha is that line there consisting of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:28.640
points, and the tangent conic is, well, it has&nbsp;
quite a different shape. In this case, it kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:28.640 --> 00:35:41.840
of a parabolic thing opening upwards, now still&nbsp;
touching there. Also goes through these points.

00:35:41.840 --> 00:35:52.840
So those are the zero, first, and second&nbsp;
tangents to the cubic at the point two.

00:35:52.840 --> 00:35:56.600
So, this is obviously so much fun you're going&nbsp;
to want to do this yourselves. You've already&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:56.600 --> 00:36:03.720
calculated, I hope, the tangents to p at 1&nbsp;
and -1, as well as the ones that we've done&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:03.720 --> 00:36:11.240
today. So please construct integer graphs&nbsp;
for the tangents to p at 1 and -1. So make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:11.240 --> 00:36:24.840
exact corresponding pictures for the tangents&nbsp;
at 1 and also at -1. It's very satisfying,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:24.840 --> 00:36:30.160
and it's calculus! If you want to have&nbsp;
something that is a little bit more smooth,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:30.160 --> 00:36:35.400
you can do a little bit more work, and you can&nbsp;
fill in some points by adding some more rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:41.280
points, maybe at halves. If you want to be more&nbsp;
ambitious, you can divide each one up into four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:41.280 --> 00:36:50.000
plot them all, get some nice pictures—everything&nbsp;
can be done by hand, you don't need any artistic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:59.360
ability. Just remember we're only using line&nbsp;
segments to join the dots. So this is pretty cool,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:04.840
and there's more cool stuff. In fact, we're&nbsp;
going to see this cubic again—there's something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:11.280
really remarkable about this cubic, well, in&nbsp;
fact, about cubics in general. But to prepare&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:17.960
the way for that, I think next time we'll&nbsp;
talk about lines and parabolas. The first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:17.960 --> 00:37:24.280
tangents—tangent lines—are lines, they're&nbsp;
pretty easy to understand. Tangent conics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:24.280 --> 00:37:31.800
are always these parabolas, and we're going&nbsp;
to have to know a little bit about parabolas.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:37.960
We'll study them algebraically and draw some&nbsp;
pictures, so I hope you'll join me for that.

00:37:37.960 --> 00:37:49.280
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

